---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="450,000 Civilians. One Island. One War. | Unmuting Ryukyu">

	<article>

		<!-- ARTICLE HEADER -->
		<header style="padding:72px 32px 56px;background:#1C2C4F;position:relative;overflow:hidden;border-bottom:4px solid #8B1D25;">
			<div style="position:absolute;inset:0;z-index:0;background:linear-gradient(135deg, #1C2C4F 0%, #0d1a30 100%);"></div>
			<div style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:5px;height:100%;background:#8B1D25;z-index:2;"></div>
			<div style="max-width:840px;margin:0 auto;position:relative;z-index:2;">
				<div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:12px;margin-bottom:20px;">
					<span style="display:inline-block;background:#8B1D25;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;padding:4px 12px;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;">History</span>
					<span style="color:#8B9BB8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;">March 2026</span>
				</div>
				<h1 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:clamp(26px,5vw,44px);font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;line-height:1.25;">450,000 Civilians. One Island. One War.</h1>
				<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:16px;margin:0 0 16px 0;max-width:620px;line-height:1.8;">They were not soldiers. They had no weapons. Yet 450,000 civilians on this tiny island became pawns in a game of empires — and one in four of them never came home.</p>
				<p style="color:#8B9BB8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:13px;margin:0;">By <a href="/about/" style="color:#D4C9BC;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Shohei Toguchi</a></p>
			</div>
		</header>

		<!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
		<div style="padding:72px 32px 96px;background:#F0EBE3;">
			<div style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;">

				<!-- Watch on YouTube CTA -->
				<div style="background:#1C2C4F;padding:20px 28px;margin-bottom:56px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:space-between;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:16px;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;">
					<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:13px;margin:0;">Watch the full short documentary on YouTube</p>
					<a href="https://www.youtube.com/@letsgokinawa" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="text-decoration:none;display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;background:#8B1D25;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-weight:700;padding:10px 20px;border-radius:2px;font-size:12px;letter-spacing:0.05em;">
						<svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><path d="M23.498 6.186a3.016 3.016 0 0 0-2.122-2.136C19.505 3.545 12 3.545 12 3.545s-7.505 0-9.377.505A3.017 3.017 0 0 0 .502 6.186C0 8.07 0 12 0 12s0 3.93.502 5.814a3.016 3.016 0 0 0 2.122 2.136c1.871.505 9.376.505 9.376.505s7.505 0 9.377-.505a3.015 3.015 0 0 0 2.122-2.136C24 15.93 24 12 24 12s0-3.93-.502-5.814zM9.545 15.568V8.432L15.818 12l-6.273 3.568z"/></svg>
						Watch on YouTube →
					</a>
				</div>

				<!-- Article Content -->
				<div style="font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;color:#4A3F3B;font-size:16px;line-height:1.95;">

					<!-- Stat callout -->
					<div style="background:#1C2C4F;padding:40px;margin-bottom:48px;text-align:center;border-top:4px solid #C8A86A;">
						<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:clamp(48px,8vw,80px);font-weight:900;color:#C8A86A;margin:0;line-height:1;letter-spacing:-0.02em;">450,000</p>
						<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:14px;margin:8px 0 0 0;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;">Civilians on Okinawa in 1945</p>
					</div>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">The Island That Was Used</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						Most people know Okinawa as a vacation destination — blue water, coral reefs, the quiet pace of island life. But in 1945, this same island was home to 450,000 civilians who had absolutely no say in what was about to happen to them.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						The Imperial Japanese military made a decision that would define Okinawa forever: the island would not be defended. It would be <em>used</em>. Every civilian, every child, every elderly farmer — they were all part of a calculation made in Tokyo. A number in a strategy called <strong>"Suteishi"</strong>.
					</p>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:48px 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">What Is "Suteishi"?</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						In Go — the ancient board game — a <em>suteishi</em> is a stone you deliberately sacrifice. Not because it has no value. But because losing it strategically benefits the bigger game.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						The Imperial Headquarters in Tokyo applied this logic to Okinawa. The island's 32nd Army, under General Ushijima, was ordered to fight for as long as possible — not to win, but to delay. To make the American invasion so costly that the mainland of Japan could prepare its final defense.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						<strong>The 450,000 civilians were not collateral damage. They were the shield.</strong>
					</p>

					<!-- Quote block -->
					<blockquote style="border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;margin:0 0 40px 0;padding:20px 28px;background:#fff;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;">
						<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:18px;color:#1C2C4F;line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic;">"Okinawa was designated as a sacrificial stone in a game of Go. A stone thrown away to save the King."</p>
					</blockquote>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">What Happened to the Civilians</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						When the battle began on April 1, 1945, those 450,000 people had nowhere to go. The island is only 60 miles long. There was no evacuation plan. There was no safety zone.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						They hid in caves as 600,000 naval shells fell. They ran south as the front collapsed. They were caught between two armies who both considered them secondary to military objectives. And when Japanese soldiers retreated into civilian shelters, the distinction between battlefield and refugee camp ceased to exist entirely.
					</p>

					<!-- Stats grid -->
					<div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(200px,1fr));gap:16px;margin:0 0 48px 0;">
						<div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:24px;text-align:center;border-top:3px solid #8B1D25;">
							<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:36px;font-weight:900;color:#8B1D25;margin:0;line-height:1;">1 in 4</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;margin:8px 0 0 0;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Okinawans killed</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:24px;text-align:center;border-top:3px solid #1C2C4F;">
							<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:36px;font-weight:900;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0;line-height:1;">~100k</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;margin:8px 0 0 0;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Civilian deaths</p>
						</div>
						<div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:24px;text-align:center;border-top:3px solid #8B1D25;">
							<p style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:36px;font-weight:900;color:#8B1D25;margin:0;line-height:1;">82</p>
							<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:12px;margin:8px 0 0 0;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Days of battle</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">The Scar That Remains</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						The battle ended on June 23, 1945. But for Okinawa, the logic of "Suteishi" never truly ended.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						Today, 70% of all US military facilities in Japan are concentrated on Okinawa — an island that makes up just 0.6% of Japan's total land area. The same strategic calculus that made Okinawa expendable in 1945 continues to make it "indispensable" today.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 48px 0;">
						The 450,000 civilians of 1945 have become the 1.4 million Okinawans of today. And they still live with the consequence of being someone else's Suteishi.
					</p>

					<!-- Learn More -->
					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:28px 32px;margin-bottom:0;">
						<p style="color:#1C2C4F;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Go Deeper</p>
						<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.85;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Want the full story of the Battle of Okinawa? Read our in-depth documentary article covering all 10 realities of Operation Iceberg.</p>
						<a href="/blog/battle-of-okinawa/" style="text-decoration:none;color:#8B1D25;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:13px;letter-spacing:0.05em;">Read: Operation Iceberg — 10 Realities →</a>
					</div>

				</div>

